	<div class="comment byuser comment-author-teorth bypostauthor odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 vcard" id="comment-631">
		<div class="comment-metadata">
			<p class="comment-permalink"><a href="http://terrytao.wordpress.com/2007/04/13/compressed-sensing-and-single-pixel-cameras/#comment-631" title="Permalink to this comment">23 April, 2007 at 7:37 am</a></p>
			<p class="comment-author"><strong class="fn"><a href='http://www.math.ucla.edu/~tao' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Terence Tao</a></strong></p>
			 
		</div>
		
		<div class="comment-content">
			<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/3c795880f3b73784a9b75fbff3772701?s=32&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-32' height='32' width='32' />			<p>Dear RD,</p>
<p>Suppose you are given a matrix A and a vector b and want to solve the problem &#8220;find the sparsest vector x for which Ax=b&#8221;.</p>
<p>For certain matrices A (basically, those in which there are plenty of linear dependencies between a relatively small number of columns) this problem is NP-hard.</p>
<p>What the work of ourselves and others shows is that for other types of matrices A (where the columns are close to being orthogonal, e.g. random matrices typically satisfy this), the problem can be solved in polynomial time by linear programming methods.</p>
<p>Unfortunately, these two classes of matrices seem to be totally disjoint, so there is no obvious progress on <img src='http://l.wordpress.com/latex.php?latex=P+%5Cneq+NP&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=545454&#038;s=0' alt='P \neq NP' title='P \neq NP' class='latex' /> here.  As I said in an earlier comment, this situation (NP-hard in worst case, P in average case) seems to be rather common.</p>

<div class="pd-rating" id="pd_rating_holder_132742_comm_631"></div><script type="text/javascript" charset="utf-8"><!--//--><![CDATA[//><!--
