<p>Sorry for the above message and thanks a lot for the help :) I will just type my question again:<br />
Regarding your comment on high-dimensional geometry, a couple of months ago, I was actually playing around with the angle <img src='http://l.wordpress.com/latex.php?latex=%5Ctheta&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=545454&#038;s=0' alt='\theta' title='\theta' class='latex' /> between one fixed vector and another randomly picked vector on n-dim unit ball and trying to calculate the probability<br />
<img src='http://l.wordpress.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathbb+P%7D%28+%5Ccos%28%5Ctheta%29+%5Cgeq+1%2Fn%5E%7B0.5-%5Cepsilon%7D%29&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=545454&#038;s=0' alt='{\mathbb P}( \cos(\theta) \geq 1/n^{0.5-\epsilon})' title='{\mathbb P}( \cos(\theta) \geq 1/n^{0.5-\epsilon})' class='latex' />, I found when <img src='http://l.wordpress.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cepsilon+%3E+0&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=545454&#038;s=0' alt='\epsilon &gt; 0' title='\epsilon &gt; 0' class='latex' />, this probability decays to zero exponentially fast with n, and if <img src='http://l.wordpress.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cepsilon+%3C+0&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=545454&#038;s=0' alt='\epsilon &lt; 0' title='\epsilon &lt; 0' class='latex' />, it goes to one. Only if <img src='http://l.wordpress.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cepsilon%3D0&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=545454&#038;s=0' alt='\epsilon=0' title='\epsilon=0' class='latex' />, there is a nontrivial probability around 0.1576 and 0.1675 asymptotically. I couldn&#8217;t get a good interpretation of what is happening when dimension is high and why <img src='http://l.wordpress.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cepsilon%3D0&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=545454&#038;s=0' alt='\epsilon=0' title='\epsilon=0' class='latex' /> is special. It looks like the surface area of the unit ball is becoming more and more concentrated around the equator when n grows big. I&#8217;m interested to know more about its relationship to the law of large numbers and more generally about high dimensional geometry. It will be great if you could point me to  any reference or explain briefly. Thanks so much!!</p>

