			<p class="comment-author"><strong class="fn">Mark Meckes</strong></p>
			 
		</div>
		
		<div class="comment-content">
			<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/42e6d6b66c0dcd704d27373818e6994f?s=32&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-32' height='32' width='32' />			<p>Andy: </p>
<p>The best-known application in high-dimensional geometry of the phenomenon you&#8217;ve observed is Dvoretzky&#8217;s theorem (in a given proof by Vitali Milman in the early 1970s).  Possibly the most accessible reference for this is Lectures 7-9 of K. Ball, &#8220;An elementary introduction to modern convex geometry&#8221;, in <a href="http://www.cambridge.org/catalogue/catalogue.asp?isbn=9780521629621" rel="nofollow">this volume</a>.</p>

