	<div class="comment even thread-even depth-1 vcard" id="comment-724">
		<div class="comment-metadata">
			<p class="comment-permalink"><a href="http://terrytao.wordpress.com/2007/04/13/compressed-sensing-and-single-pixel-cameras/#comment-724" title="Permalink to this comment">27 April, 2007 at 7:28 pm</a></p>
			<p class="comment-author"><strong class="fn">Kaleberg</strong></p>
			 
		</div>
		
		<div class="comment-content">
			<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/670e70e1c5b3419b2b6fc500d89dab22?s=32&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-32' height='32' width='32' />			<p>This approach reminds me of early X ray astronomy sensors, before they developed grazing lenses. They used a sheet of X ray blocking metal with a random pattern of holes punched in it and rotated the sheet while collecting a single pixel of data, the overall intensity. I think they could also move the sheet further and closer to the single sensor in a sort of &#8220;trombone&#8221; arrangement. I never worked with this, but I had a roommate who worked on the SAS-C team, and he tried explaining how the sensor, or perhaps an improved sensor, might work.</p>
<p>I&#8217;m not sure of the mathematics of this approach, since their &#8220;wavelet basis&#8221; was rather simple, and not completely random. Still, they did get the sensor count down to one, they traded off satellite based computing for ground computing, and they did get some neat images, included Cygnus X-1.</p>

