	<div class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1 vcard" id="comment-5226">
		<div class="comment-metadata">
			<p class="comment-permalink"><a href="http://terrytao.wordpress.com/2007/04/13/compressed-sensing-and-single-pixel-cameras/#comment-5226" title="Permalink to this comment">29 July, 2007 at 3:58 am</a></p>
			<p class="comment-author"><strong class="fn"><a href='http://blog.xquant.net' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>nicolas</a></strong></p>
			 
		</div>
		
		<div class="comment-content">
			<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/91f975afaf89b2bcd5a34722ab4c8505?s=32&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-32' height='32' width='32' />			<p>I am very thrilled to discover that you are interested in Information theory problems. being a mathematician by education I have way too often been put off by professionals who like theories not for their power, but for their complexity.</p>
<p>This is not the case for Information theory, which I view as one of the biggest problems around. It is transverse, potent, and critical in many other areas of science.</p>
<p>Interestingly I tried to develop sensor compressing on my own in 1994 when I started engineering school, but did not have the necessary math skills to develop it. Also, I had few ways to reach the math literature we now have on the internet, and even fewer ways to connect with like-minded individuals.<br />
Now a Fields medalist has a blog, and I find, serendipitously, that he works on a subject that interests me&#8230;.</p>
<p>Nicolas</p>

