	<div class="comment odd alt depth-2 vcard" id="comment-40984">
		<div class="comment-metadata">
			<p class="comment-permalink"><a href="http://terrytao.wordpress.com/2007/04/13/compressed-sensing-and-single-pixel-cameras/#comment-40984" title="Permalink to this comment">11 August, 2009 at 9:50 pm</a></p>
			<p class="comment-author"><strong class="fn">AJ</strong></p>
			 
		</div>
		
		<div class="comment-content">
			<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/?s=32&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-32' height='32' width='32' />			<p>This is only for response to coding theory.<br />
Even though binary codes have been well studied. They are of limited use. Codes have to be carved from lattices in real world. </p>
<p>One can life the binary codes (or finite field codes) to complex numbers. It may no longer be non-linear. An important problem is to lift the codes so that<br />
1) they are linear<br />
2) if the hamming distance is small b/w the finite field codewords, then their euclidean distance have to be larger. This strategy comes close to achieving the best possoble performance. It is extremely hard to do with finite field codes, but an elementary exercise in function field codes (convolutional codes)</p>

