	<div class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 vcard" id="comment-40982">
		<div class="comment-metadata">
			<p class="comment-permalink"><a href="http://terrytao.wordpress.com/2007/04/13/compressed-sensing-and-single-pixel-cameras/#comment-40982" title="Permalink to this comment">11 August, 2009 at 6:36 pm</a></p>
			<p class="comment-author"><strong class="fn">AJ</strong></p>
			 
		</div>
		
		<div class="comment-content">
			<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/?s=32&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-32' height='32' width='32' />			<p>Sparsity implies low entropy. But Low entropy does not imply sparsity. To information theorists entropy is object of interest.</p>
<p>CS is a curious tool in signal processing. But it is unclear whether there is a generalization of CS to make it related to entropy of sources. If so this generalization of CS would be a powerful tool in information theory.</p>

