	<div class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 vcard" id="comment-41693">
		<div class="comment-metadata">
			<p class="comment-permalink"><a href="http://terrytao.wordpress.com/2007/04/13/compressed-sensing-and-single-pixel-cameras/#comment-41693" title="Permalink to this comment">4 October, 2009 at 1:17 pm</a></p>
			<p class="comment-author"><strong class="fn">AJ</strong></p>
			 
		</div>
		
		<div class="comment-content">
			<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/?s=32&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-32' height='32' width='32' />			<p>Professor:<br />
Conceptually your answer makes sense. However, the reason I have specifically asked this question is because of the existence of locally decodable codes and the applicability of CS technique to coding theory.</p>
<p>In coding theory, y = Gx +n is received vector where G is the generator, x is message, n is noise.</p>
<p>Typically one has to process all bits of y to get reliable reconstruction of x.</p>
<p>However LDC offers the following flexibility:<br />
Suppose only bit location i of x has to be be found, a q query LDC needs to access only q locations of y.</p>
<p>Existence of good LDCs have implications in complexity theory. Since CS offers good decoding ability, I was wondering if bounds in CS could be transferred to bounds in LDCs.</p>
<p><a href="http://research.microsoft.com/en-us/um/people/yekhanin/papers/nice_pir_limits.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://research.microsoft.com/en-us/um/people/yekhanin/papers/nice_pir_limits.pdf</a></p>
<p>However known LDCs are non-random. However it might still not be a problem in transferring CS techniques because of the following result:<br />
<a href="http://www2.computer.org/portal/web/csdl/doi/10.1109/FOCS.2007.8" rel="nofollow">http://www2.computer.org/portal/web/csdl/doi/10.1109/FOCS.2007.8</a></p>
<p>I am working along this line of reasoning. I was wondering if my ideas make sense to you and whether it would be worth proceeding in this route.</p>
<p>Thank you,<br />
sincerely,</p>

<div class="pd-rating" id="pd_rating_holder_132742_comm_41693"></div><script type="text/javascript" charset="utf-8"><!--//--><![CDATA[//><!--
